{"questionId":"3857332","questionHtml":"<p>A simple pendulum oscillates with frequency <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi></math>. The length of the pendulum is halved. What is the new frequency of the pendulum?</p>\n<p><br>A.&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>f</mi></math></p>\n<p>B.&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi>f</mi></math></p>\n<p>C.&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>f</mi><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac></math></p>\n<p>D.&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>B</p>","meta":{"questionId":"3857332","referenceCode":"23M.1A.SL.TZ1.26","subjectId":"59-dp-physics-first-assessment-2025","title":"A simple pendulum oscillates with frequency f. The length of the pendulum is halved. What is the new frequency of the pendulum? A. 2f B. 2f C. f2 D. f2","paper":"1A","level":"SL","questionNumber":"26","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["C. Wave behaviour","C.1 Simple harmonic motion"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}